body.listDescription:
This list contains a collective of Ethereum's active core protocol contributors, which today comprises 152 individuals. These individuals have at least 6 months of continuous contributions focused on the following areas:

1. Ethereum L1 core protocol maintenance and development
Includes production client implementations like Erigon, Geth, Hyperledger Besu, Lighthouse, Lodestar, Nethermind, Nimbus, Prysm and Teku, as well as client testing/security/infra which supports these implementations, and finally coordination work related to upgrades and maintenance

2. Research and implementation experiments related to potential protocol changes/refinements
Examples: verkle tries, portal network, EVM improvements: Ipsilon, consensus work, cryptography, mechanism design & resource pricing

3. Spec work resulting from the above

Astute observers will note that this list only contains one project - Protocol Guild. How can this be, you may ask?

The Protocol Guild provides a single high-signal list of Ethereum's core protocol contributors, that the ecosystem can use to channel public goods funding towards. This list is curated by these core protocol contributors themselves, providing very high accuracy assurances, given that they have significantly higher context and domain expertise compared to any external curator. You can learn more about the curation process here: https://protocol-guild.readthedocs.io/en/latest/4-roles-expectations.html

It should be noted that any funds sent to the Protocol Guild are vested directly to Ethereum's core protocol contributors over time, creating long-term incentives for such stewardship while facilitating knowledge handover. You can learn more about the Guild's smart contract architecture here: https://protocol-guild.readthedocs.io/en/latest/3-smart-contract.html
body.impactEvaluationDescription:
How does the work of the Protocol Guild relate to Optimism? 

As a rollup, Optimism leverages Ethereum for settlement & security assurances. It also uses several core infrastructure components (client implementations, specifications, test suites, etc.) developed and maintained by Protocol Guild contributors over the years. Optimism also directly benefits from protocol upgrades such as proto-danksharding (EIP-4844), which will significantly reduce the fees its users need to pay.

All of this work supports a mutual relationship:

- Ethereum provides an infrastructural foundation with particular characteristics (eg. social, political, technical, economic) that only it can uniquely provide

- Optimism produces lower-cost blockspace that the base layer is not able to provide, while still inheriting some of its characteristics. The project also has more space for experimentation eg. integrating infra funding circuits into the blockspace production process.

Given the foundational impact Ethereum's core protocol contributors have had on the OP stack, I am assigning the maximum possible allocation for a single project - 5m OP. 

However, I will not personally vote for the Protocol Guild, due to a conflict of interest, as indicated here: https://gov.optimism.io/t/badgeholder-conflict-of-interest-disclosures/5569/46?u=cheeky-gorilla ✌️

body.listDescription:
Optimism is designed to be as simple as possible for the featureset it provides. Ideally, Optimism should be composed of the minimum number of moving parts required for a secure, scalable, and flexible L2 system. This simplicity gives Optimism's design a number of significant advantages over other more complex L2 constructions.

Simplicity reduces engineering overhead, which in turn means we can spend our time working on new features instead of re-creating existing ones. Optimism prefers to use existing battle-tested Ethereum code and infrastructure where possible. The most visible example of this philosophy in practice is the choice to use Geth as Optimism's client software.

When dealing with critical infrastructure, simplicity is also security. Every line of code we write is an opportunity to introduce unintentional bugs. A simple protocol means there's less code to write and, as a result, less surface area for potential mistakes. A clean and minimal codebase is also more accessible to external contributors and auditors. All of this serves to maximize the security and correctness of the Optimism protocol.

Simplicity is also important for the long-term vision of Optimism. By limiting the amount of code that we write on top of Ethereum tooling, we're able to spend most of our time working directly with existing codebases. Engineering effort that goes into Optimism can also directly benefit Ethereum, and vice versa. This will only become more pronounced as the Optimism protocol solidifies and existing resources can be redirected towards core Ethereum infrastructure

This list includes projects actively using Account Abstraction themselves, as well as those enabling people to build with and better understand AA / ERC-4337 broadly speaking.

body.impactEvaluationDescription: My methodology is pretty simplistic and draws directly from the "Funding Gap = Impact - Profit" framework outlined by the Optimism Team. I have assigned each project a "public good / needs the funding" rating as well as a "retroactive impact to Optimism" rating, and have weighted the total allocation to incorporate the former as 1/3 of the aggregate score and the latter as 2/3. You can see my full scoring in the linked Google Sheet. Note that this is an early attempt at a list based on my perception alone, and I encourage feedback/additional data points (as well as projects I'm missing here!). I fully expect to be updating my list ahead of the deadline.

body.listDescription:
All of my lists for RPGF3 will be highlighting impact that concerns end users/citizens of the Optimism ecosystem. 
My main question going into all of this was: What kind of culture will Optimism offer all of these humans? 

To answer this, I have been reading RPGF3 applications with a focus on education, news, arts, social media, local efforts, identity, reputation, roles, etc.

I wanted to know what Optimism can offer humans *beyond* bits and coins. 

THIS LIST is about educational resources and efforts. 

Open access to knowledge and skills is a prerequisite for individuals and societies to evolve. 
It is necessary for a person to enter the spaces of their choice and apply themselves in meaningful ways.
Without such free opportunity, there can be no democracy, transparency, freedom, collaboration, etc.

The list focuses broadly on web3 education. Perspective is necessary, both to become a professional and to stay human. 

The list only includes resources in English language - I highly value efforts in other languages as well, but I will look at them separately.

body.listDescription:
This is a list of projects that create opensource code that is here to stay and is not limited by any business source license or other limitations. The code must be truly opensource and not depend on any single company to exist in order to maintain its impact. The project must have had a measurable impact on the ecosystem.

DISCLAIMER: Author of the list is also founder of rotki, which is a project satisfying the requirements and is part of the list.

Notes: 

- This is version 1 of the list. Since lists can't be edited I may create more versions if I find that more projects fit the list or that listed projects do not belong here.
- No specific funds recommendation given. Badgeholders should use their own due dilligence and opinion there. The list simply divides 30m $OP by the number of projects in the list.
body.impactEvaluationDescription:
The impact was evaluated by:

- Checking that the project produced truly opensource code. The definition of opensource is that of FSF and OSI. Anything else is just source available and not opensource.
- The impact of the code must be measurable and applicable even if the company/team behind it ceases to exist. Otherwise it's not really a project creating opensource code as a gift to the world but just using the term opensource as marketing.
- If the project is bootstrapped and has raised no VC funding then extra points are given. As this means that it is harder to be captured by external interests and remains truly owned by its users, by its community and the world.

For almost all of the projects listed I have either somehow used them and measured impact myself, or have seen trusted friends and/or colleagues use them and heard positive feedback.

body.listDescription:
Open source applications and application development tools deployed to OP Stack chains that directly contribute to revenues for the collective via gas consumption. RPGF sustainability is paramount - our community will be able to incentivize public goods development long term only if the collective is generating revenues. Therefore this list attempts to shine a spotlight on public goods that are generating revenue at the app layer for the collective by attracting activity and gas consumption on OP Stack chains.
Disclosure link: https://gov.optimism.io/t/badgeholder-conflict-of-interest-disclosures/5569/54

body.impactEvaluationDescription: This list assumes 20% (6M) of total RPGF funds is allocated to application layer projects deployed on the OP Stack. Projects are roughly categorized into five groups based on gas consumption using ethereum-etl and Chainbase queries derived from the contract addresses available in applicant's forms and their Github repos. I did my best to query unlisted project contract addresses created by factory contracts as well, borrowing from existing Dune dashboards in some cases. Projects in between two categories that are nonprofit or do not have any form of value extraction implemented were bumped up, while others were bumped down if there was heavy extraction. Must be deployed to OP Mainnet, Base, or another OP Stack chain, and contracts must be open sourced via Github repo or verification on a block explorer, Sourcify, or another service. Attempted to include all application layer projects that have generated meaningful sequencer revenue, although some applications like NFT projects and memecoins are excluded from this group if they did not deploy anything other than their token.

The Impact evaluation criteria used here is explicitly about how the token project itself has contributed to the Optimism ecosystem; 

Has there been any co-incentives from this token? Has their community joined the Optimism community? How have the communications from both teams happened? etc.

body.impactEvaluationDescription:
At EthernautDAO, led by Alejandro Santander (Ethernaut) and Gonzalo Diez (Gonna), we focus on supporting projects that align with our mission and show potential for impact. Our voting list helps identify and support these projects using a direct evaluation method.

Our evaluation process is simple:

1. **Initial Scoring**: We rate each project from 1-15 based on our understanding of its potential and areas that need work.
2. **Average Scores**: We average these scores to get a fair overall rating.
3. **Team Engagement**: We talk to project teams to find out what they need for the next semester. We adjust scores by adding 0.5 points for every 100k in funding they require.
4. **Funds Distribution**: We then distribute 10 million OP tokens according to these scores, ensuring fair resource allocation based on each project's merit and needs.

For more details on how we calculate these scores, see the linked document.

Note: We don't vote on projects listed in the “Conflict” column. For these, we only suggest a possible allocation based on our knowledge of the project and its impact.

Categories:
- Contributors were assessed along the lines of ONE (creator or company), FEW (team or DAO), MANY (collective or delegation)
- Beneficiaries were assessed along the lines of Few (small delegations or DAOs) and Many (other builders and users)
- Good Governors were assessed as Yes (likely to vote with or delegate OP tokens) or No (not likely to actively govern with OP tokens or no retro OP/Governance contribution highlighted in application)

None/One/Few/Many
NONE 0/0/0/0

Total weight check: 1.0

The contributor tracks in the Optimism Collective are OG community-led initiatives that generate value daily for a diversity of profiles that engage with the official channels of the Optimism Ecosystem, be it protocol developers, engineers setting up their nodes, governance participants, or new projects building on the OP Chains. The sustainable decentralization of these efforts is fundamental to ensure continuous growth of the Ecosystem and has served as a stepping stone for long-term OP contributors.

Disclaimer: Through the analysis of the data of these projects I found out I'm included in the Optimism Translators because I translated 0.42% of the Bedrock docs into Spanish, so I can't and won't vote for that project. However, I AM including a recommended amount based on a rigorous methodology I hope will serve others: https://gov.optimism.io/t/badgeholder-conflict-of-interest-disclosures/5569/57?u=launamu
body.impactEvaluationDescription:
Each category uses a distinct set of criteria and metrics for evaluation, tailored to the specific objectives and activities within the Optimism ecosystem. Having worked previously in Ops I have also included some bias into behaviours I believe should be rewarded in each category to incentivize the continuous good performance (or improvement) of contributors.

1. **Numba NERDs**: Focuses on deep dive analyses, utilization in discussions, decision-making impact, recommendations to ecosystem partners, and governance data accessibility. Evaluation involves counting analyses, tracking mentions, assessing decisions' influence, evaluating recommendations, and analyzing data accessibility. Ratings are given on a 1-5 scale.

2. **Optimism Translators**: Involves calculating the average number of words per article, total words translated per language, and categorizing languages based on rarity and speaking population. The evaluation incorporates multipliers for word counts, rarity levels, and speaking populations, leading to a final amount combining Help Center and Article OP amounts.

3. **TechNERDs**: Assesses time saved for developers, response time efficiency, support ticket resolution, user support rating, community engagement, innovation, and overall ecosystem health. Metrics include hours saved, response times, ticket resolutions, user ratings, community engagement, and innovation contributions.

4. **SupNERDs**: Calculates total hours worked based on messages sent and average messages per hour. It evaluates support and safety, user experience, adoption, and language support through resolved queries, user ratings, engagement metrics, and multilingual support services.

This list encompasses the application of the following methodology as conceived and applied by mel.eth as could best be derived from the 104 Collective Governance related applications reviewed.

body.impactEvaluationDescription:

- Beneficiaries were assessed along the lines of Few (small delegations or DAOs) and Many (other builders and users)
- Good Governors were assessed as Yes (likely to vote with or delegate OP tokens) or No (not likely to actively govern with OP tokens or no retro OP/Governance contribution highlighted in application)

body.listDescription: Recognizes the impactful projects that have significantly contributed to the Ethereum wallet space. This list scope relates to wallets application and wallet specific dev tooling. Some projects made the list as wallet companion tool, add-ons that improve wallet safety and user-experience.
body.impactEvaluationDescription:
Author and disclaimer: I have experience in wallet development in account abstraction and have been working in the space for the last 2 years. I have a conflict of interest with Candide, a project in the list that I will not be voting for.

About: I have created a list that recognizes the impactful projects that have significantly contributed to the wallet space. The list scope include end-user wallets, and wallet specific dev tooling. Some projects made the list as companions for wallets that help in safety. Dashboards, general dev-tooling, and other helpful tools are not in the scope of this list.

Impact Evaluation: I have spent a considerable amount of time looking at each project, looking at github, their apps, and on-chain metrics if available, and gave a score to each category. The list scores a impact evaluation under 3 main vectors: impact (4 points), profit gap (2 points), and open source (2 points). I have deemed that an evaluation counting pixel metrics are impossible to compare between projects, and thus aimed it is an subjective judgment based on my time spend reviewing each applicant. Under each project, a small comment / phrase to review. 

Developer Ecosystem (category) 4/4
- Did this project resulted in significant number of developers / projects building wallets on Optimism? 2 points
- Did this contribution introduce innovative tooling to build wallets on Optimism? 2 points

End-user Experience (category) 4/4
- Did this project resulted in an increase of onchain activity or active usage? 2 points
- Did this project improved the user experience significantly on Optimism? 2 points

I gave 4 points on Impact because I needed a scale to score teams that had high impact vs low/medium impact on Optimism. Impact has the highest total of points as I deem to give weight more to it than other factors. 

Profit Gap (all projects) 3/3
- Has this project impact been larger than the revenue and grants they received from the collective? 3 points (small, medium, large gaps)

When giving a score on the profit gap, the evaluation was on impact minus profit collected = profit gap. I estimated a project on the category they applied to, and then tried to estimate the profit they could have received. More weight has been given to impact than profit because of our personal ability to judge better on impact. We have no way to know how much profit a team have made, hence the 3 points

Open Source (all projects) 2/2
- Is this project a high quality open source code? 1 point
- has this project been actively maintained? 1 point

I gave open source a total of 2 points to score to judge both quality and active maintenance. IMHO open source is a important part of being "a public good" in software. RPGF3 expanded beyond just open software, to include more categories that had an impact on Optimism (education, end-consumer apps, etc..). Hence 4 points for Impact, and 2 points for Open Source.

Total allocation
Improved Wallet safety, user experience and development remains one of the biggest challenge that Ethereum and its ecosystem faces. Advocating for 6m (20%) of the total allocation. I am biased as I work to improve the wallet space.

body.listDescription:
A list of the Africa based projects have been creating impact and contributing to the development of the ecosystem.

It's important to note that in the current stage of the African ecosystem, when ETHEREUM grows => OPTIMISM grows. 

Why? Ethereum mainnet has been predominantly unusable due to high gas fees, and the center of gravity in the Ethereum community has been heavily disconnected from Africa. So whenever community builders do meaningful work to train talent and grow the Ethereum ecosystem on the continent, they make it directly possible to grow Optimism. Without that type of work, Optimism wouldn't stand a decent chance to penetrate the African market. When evaluating projects, I assume whoever is growing Ethereum is also growing Optimism.
body.impactEvaluationDescription:
I have included only projects that I can personally attest have been doing meaningful work for longer than a year.

Criteria:
1. Track record of execution (length of track record and depth of impact)
2. Mission / vision alignment with Ethereum and Optimism, based on strategic and operational decisions the team has been making
3. Where in the lifecycle the project is

I am allocating 50% of my total OP budget to Africa specific projects. This is because the work of so many has been overlooked and unnoticed by the majority of the Ethereum and Optimism communities, and it's important to put significant effort to retroactively recognize all that work.
